# Methods and Findings 
#Social Network Analysis

#The study uses network analysis technique to investigate the relationship between Alex's choices of schools based on degree and the choices of schools based on safety - the schools with low crime rate. Network analysis involves visualizing the interconnection between separate entities.

#To create a social network model, it is necessary to first create a social network data set. A social network data set contains nodes and targets. The codes below develops nodes. The nodes represent the origin of the mapping points. The origin of the mapping points for study are the cities with schools that are Alex's choices based on the degrees. 

#In a social network graph, the nodes represent the objects that the network seeks to explore their interconnection. The nodes represent the cities (CITY) with the schools of Alex's choice. The nodes are preferences, a list containing the list of cities. The block of codes below extracts the nodes. 
id<-1:length(Alexchoice$CITY)
CITY1<-Alexchoice$CITY
nodes1<-tibble(id,CITY1)
head(nodes1)

#Developing edge list
#The next step of building a social network  model involves developing edge list. Edge list is a data frame with two or more columns. One of the columns in a edge list contains the source of connection, and the other column contains the nodes. The source of connection is the origin of the network model, while the nodes are the targets for the connection. The network model will visualize the relationship between the nodes and the target columns. The data frame contains a mapping of the mapping of the choices based on degrees to the choices based on the safety of the schools. 

sources<-Alexchoice$INSTNM
Destination<-Alexchoice1$INSTNM
Weight<-Alexchoice1$Rape1
edgeList1<-tibble(sources,Destination,Weight)
edgeList1<-edgeList1%>%
  group_by(sources)
head(edgeList1)

#Developing a social network model
#A social network data frame is created from the edge list. The social network data frame contains the networks. The networks are the connections between one node (CITY/school) to the other. In addition, the data frame demonstrate the frequency of the interconnection between the nodes or how frequent one node connects to the other.

networks<-graph.data.frame(edgeList1,directed = T)
networks

#The aim of the project was to identify the institutions/universities that  are considered safe by Alex. The criteria is based on the number of rape cases. Universities or institutions with low rape cases are considered to be safe while the universities with high rape cases are considered to be unsafe. 
#The social network graphs only considers the institutions with relatively lower cases of rape from as low as 0 cases. In addition to visualizing the institution and their interconnections, the project also visualizes the cities with relatively lower rape cases and among Alex's choices. 
#The social networks demonstrates that there are different universities with 0 cases of rape, and fall in Alex's list of institutions.
#The corresponding specfic cities with low crime rates are Louisville, Austin, Buffalo, Greensboro, Memphis and Norfolk.
